@GovAndyBeshear just announced that he has requested an emergency disaster declaration from @POTUS to activate federal emergency response and funding for the tornado damage in Kentucky. As Dean of the House and the Kentucky Delegation, I will let the President know that we fully support this request for assistance, which is desperately needed in our Commonwealth once again.

My heart is heavy today as our region has been devastated by another deadly storm. Search and rescue efforts have been ongoing overnight in Laurel and Pulaski Counties with the death toll rising above 20 and increasing by the hour.

@KentuckyEM confirmed that the @kentuckyguard was activated to assist with emergency response and have been on the scene since this morning. They reported more than 400 homes damaged in Laurel County alone.

First Baptist Church in London, Ky is a designated shelter for individuals in need.

If you are searching for loved ones, you can call the Kentucky State Police post in London at 606-878-6622. Faith Assembly of God in London, KY is also a designated "Family Assistance Center" for individuals who want to meet with KSP in person about missing loved ones.

If you want to request a wellness check, you can call the London Emergency Operations Center at 606-878-1000.

I am grateful to our neighbors in Lexington, Louisville, Cincinnati and other parts of the state who have been assisting emergency crews in London and Somerset as well.

I was honored to meet William K. Marshall, III today, the new Director of the Federal Bureau of Prisons. @OfficialFBOP 

As Chairman of the Subcommittee that funds the BOP, we discussed some of the challenges ahead in improving operations and safety of the 122 BOP facilities. 

I highlighted the importance of moving forward with the proposed modernized prison in Letcher County and protecting the 1,300 federal employees who are working in the four existing BOP facilities in Kentucky’s 5th District: FCI Ashland, FCI Manchester, USP Big Sandy & USP McCreary. 

I look forward to working with Director Marshall as we continue the federal funding process for fiscal year 2026.

I convened a meeting this afternoon with superintendents from 25 school districts in Kentucky's 5th Congressional District, along with the Kentucky Association of School Administrators (KASA), to discuss federal funding that impacts students across our rural region. More than anything, I listened to them and their concerns about the future of vital programs and resources that directly benefit our students and the opportunities that they have access to. As I return to Washington this week, I will work to ensure that our schools and our students have the resources they need to be successful. I deeply appreciate the work of our educators and their passion to pave the path for a brighter future in southern and eastern Kentucky!

I was honored to join the ribbon-cutting celebration for Teledyne FLIR's new 13,000 sq. ft. facility at the Valley Oak Technology Complex in Pulaski County. Their impressive Black Hornet nano-drones are used by our U.S. Armed Forces. They have been operating in Somerset since 2019 and their new facility will allow them to double their workforce, which will focus on servicing, testing and training operations.

🚨@AGPamBondi announced the largest drug bust in U.S. history, targeting one of the largest drug trafficking and terrorist organizations in our country!

🚨What does that mean for Kentucky? The amount of drugs that were stopped from coming into our communities from this single drug bust was enough to kill 71% of Kentuckians. @uniteky 

🚨This historic drug bust led to the arrest of six people living in our country illegally who were running a massive drug operation. 

🚨The @DEAHQ seized a total of:
-11.5 kilos of fentanyl, including 3 million fentanyl pills – stamped as oxycodone
-$5 million in cash
-35 kilos of meth
-7.5 kilos of cocaine
-4.5 kilos of heroin
-49 rifles and pistols

As a result of the federal investigation, DEA arrested one of the leaders of the Sinaloa Cartel in Oregon, and seized illicit drugs in New Mexico, Arizona & Utah.

75,000 Americans have been dying of fentanyl-related overdose deaths each year. Fentanyl-related overdose is the leading cause of death for Americans between the ages of 18 and 34. 

Since @POTUS took office in January 2025, nearly 30 million fentanyl-laced pills have already been seized, protecting our communities and keeping these deadly pills from reaching the hands of our loved ones.

Thank you, @POTUS, @AGPamBondi, @DEAHQ and all the law enforcement officers involved in this life-saving drug bust!

Today, I hosted a roundtable discussion in Hazard with the @NashvilleCorps, @HuntingtonCorps & the Louisville Corps for our local elected leaders who serve Eastern Kentucky counties that have been impacted by recent flooding. We discussed stream cleaning, the permitting process, dredging, structural solutions, as well as river gages and sensors to protect our communities from future floods. 

We reviewed successful Army Corps projects that have helped save communities along the Cumberland River from catastrophic flooding, and the work that is still needed on the Cumberland, and additional flood control projects that are necessary on the Kentucky River and the Big Sandy River. 

On-going projects include a Kentucky River Flood Control Study and flood prevention in Beattyville, Coal Run and Paintsville, among others.

Today, my field staff set up a Mobile Office at the Pike County Library, alongside FEMA & SBA, at one of the FEMA Disaster Recovery Centers to assist individuals with the flood recovery process. My staff will be available until 5pm on Friday. Constituents can also call my offices toll free at 1-800-632-8588 for help with lost documents, veterans’ lost medals, and assistance with all federal agencies. My Mobile Office will be available in several counties in the coming days and weeks - stay tuned for details.

🚨IMPORTANT NEWS FOR KENTUCKY🚨
I’m grateful for President Trump's Expedited Major Disaster Declaration for Kentucky, which includes public assistance and individual assistance for ten counties. Additional counties may be added as assessments are completed. Our region is not only recovering from this flood; we are still rebuilding from the major floods in 2022 and 2021. Eastern Kentucky knows first-hand the importance of this federal declaration and my staff is prepared to help our people through the process, once again. Thank you, @POTUS!

The expedited counties, thus far, include: Breathitt, Clay, Harlan, Knott, Lee, Letcher, Martin, Owsley, Perry and Pike Counties for Individual Assistance. Additional counties may be added.
